follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Analog or digital outputs from instruments are sampled at regular intervals,
 typically 50 Hz when possible.
 Analog outputs are converted to digital values via analog-to-digital converters.
 The investigator's handbooks for each aircraft describe this process in
 detail, including resolution of the sampling and handling of the results.
 Often, signals from user-supplied instruments are also included in the
 measured values that are handled by the data system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The digital outputs are then recorded by the data system on the aircraft.
 Currently, this is a task of the 
\emph on

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph default

\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "NIDAS"
target "http://www.eol.ucar.edu/data/software/nidas"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
NIDAS
\end_layout

\end_inset

 system described below.
 That system also controls the sampling, time stamps, and other aspects
 of data recording.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In flight, the data are processed by the 
\emph on

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nimbus
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\emph default
 data processing program, which makes them available for display via 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "aeros"
target "http://www.eol.ucar.edu/raf/Software/aeros_dnld.html"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for real-time monitoring of measurements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Following the flight, 
\emph on
nimbus
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
nimbus
\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph default
 again processes the data.
 At this stage, measurements can be re-sampled with averaging and/or interpolati
on to produce different time frequencies, and known lags in measurements
 can be introduced to adjust measurements to a common time basis.
 As part of this processing, 
\emph on
nimbus
\emph default
 applies calibration coefficients where appropriate to convert recorded
 values (e.g., voltage) to engineering units (e.g., 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\circ}$
\end_inset

C).
 Determining or checking these calibration coefficients is part of the pre-fligh
t and post-flight procedures for each project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The output from 
\emph on
nimbus
\emph default
 is the data file that is the permanent archive from the experiment, often
 after merging in additional data sets from users that are not recorded
 in the original data file produced by 
\emph on
NIDAS.

\emph default
 These files, in NetCDF format, have headers that contain metadata on each
 measurement (such as the calibration coefficients, the instrument that
 produced the measurement, etc.).
 Many of the variables in these files are discussed in this technical note,
 but the files may also include additional project-specific measurements
 for which the NetCDF header and the project reports will be the only documentat
ion.
\end_layout

