\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu:ppmv"

\end_inset

The International Bureau of Weights and Measures recommends against use
 of units like percent or parts per million, but these are in common use
 in atmospheric chemistry and elsewhere so data files continue to use those
 units for relative humidity or the concentration of chemical species.
 Typical units are ppmv
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
ppmv
\end_layout

\end_inset

 or ppbv
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
ppbv
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for parts per million by volume or parts per billion by volume.
 Care must be taken to interpret ppbv especially, because 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

billion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 has different meaning in different languages and different countries; herein,
 1 ppbv means a volumetric ratio of 1:10
\begin_inset Formula $^{9}$
\end_inset

.
 Many measurements produce native results in terms of a mass ratio, often
 described as a mixing ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{m}$
\end_inset

 in terms of mass of the measured gas per unit mass of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

air
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (where the weight of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

air
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 does not include the variable constituents, usually only significant for
 water vapor).
 The perfect gas law relates the density ratio of two gases (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}:\rho_{2})$
\end_inset

 to the ratio of their partial pressures (
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}:p_{2}$
\end_inset

) or number densities (
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}:n_{2}$
\end_inset

), as follows:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{m}=\frac{\rho_{1}}{\rho_{2}}=\frac{p_{1}M_{1}}{p_{2}M_{2}}=\frac{n_{1}M_{1}}{n_{2}M_{2}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}$
\end_inset

 are respective molecular weights for the two gases.
 The ratio of number densities or, equivalently, partial pressures, denoted
 here as 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{v}$
\end_inset

 because it is also the volumetric mixing ratio, is related to the mass
 mixing ratio as follows:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{v}=\frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}=\left(\frac{M_{2}}{M_{1}}\right)r_{m}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

